"{\n    \"paragraphs\": [\n        \"Arctic sea ice likely reached its annual minimum extent on Sept. 19, 2023, making it the sixth-lowest year in the satellite record, according to researchers at NASA and the National Snow and Ice Data Center (NSIDC).\",\n        \"Meanwhile, Antarctic sea ice reached its lowest maximum extent on record on Sept. 10, 2023, at a time when the ice cover should have been growing at a much faster pace during the darkest and coldest months.\",\n        \"Scientists track the seasonal and annual fluctuations because sea ice shapes Earth\\u2019s polar ecosystems and plays a significant role in global climate.\",\n        \"Researchers at NSIDC and NASA use satellites to measure sea ice as it melts and refreezes. They track sea ice extent, which is defined as the total area of the ocean in which the ice cover fraction is at least 15%.\",\n        \"Between March and September 2023, the ice cover in the Arctic shrank from a peak area of 5.64 million square miles (14.62 million square kilometers) to 1.63 million square miles (4.23 million square kilometers). That\\u2019s roughly 770,000 square miles (1.99 million square kilometers) below the 1981\\u20132010 average minimum of 2.4 million square miles (6.22 million square kilometers).\",\n        \"The amount of sea ice lost was enough to cover the entire continental United States.\",\n        \"Sea ice around Antarctica reached its lowest winter maximum extent on Sept. 10, 2023, at 6.5 million square miles (16.96 million square kilometers). That\\u2019s 398,000 square miles (1.03 million square kilometers) below the previous record-low reached in 1986 \\u2013 a difference that equates to roughly the size of Texas and California combined.\",\n        \"The average maximum extent between 1981 and 2010 was 7.22 million square miles (18.71 million square kilometers). \\u201cIt\\u2019s a record-smashing sea ice low in the Antarctic,\\u201d said Walt Meier, a sea ice scientist at NSIDC. \\u201cSea ice growth appears low around nearly the whole continent as opposed to any one region.\\u201d\"\n    ]\n}"